{Known\und}
1. A{x\bar} represents a {linear combination\und}
	of {columns\und} of A.
2. {y\bar} = A{x\bar} is a {linear tranformation\und}
	From R{n\sup} to R{m\sup}
	{Range\und} of this function is Col(A) [column space of A]
3. A{x\bar}={b\bar} may have no solution (i.e. inconsistent)
	2 & 3 Imply the system is consistent {provided\und} {b\bar} {ele} Col(A)

When {no\und} solution exists, we instead try to minimize ||A{x\bar} - {b\bar}||
	(called {least\und}-{squares\und} error)

4. Choose {x\bar} to solve A{x\bar} = {b\bar}{Col(A)\sub}
						^b projected onto Col(A)
	{b\bar}{Col(A)\sub} = A{x\hat} where {x\hat} solves A{T\sup}A{x\hat}=A{T\sup}{b\hat}

{Least squares solution\und} is {x\hat} (as opposed to A{x\hat})
Least squares Error:
	||A{x\hat} - {b\bar}||
	   ^{b\bar}{Col(A)\sub}

	Note: A{T\sup}A{x\hat}=A{T\sup}{b\hat} is {always\und} consistent.
		When a {unique\und} solution exists we can write {x\hat} = (A{T\sup}A){-1\sup}A{T\sup}{b\bar}
		{Otherwise\und}
			{x\hat} = (A{T\sup}A)\\A{T\sup}{b\bar}
				^ Matlab, not Math (backslash operator)
{Linear Regression\und}
	If you are given 3+ points, it is "unlikely" that a line goes through all of them.
	
	{x\bar} = given x-coords
	{y\bar} = given y-coords
	Try to solve [x.^0 x.^1]*[b m]' = y
		^ Probably doesn't have a solution
	Instead we do:
		A = [x.^0 x.^1]
		Solve: A{T\sup}A{c\hat} = A{T\sup}{y\bar}
Example in Matlab:
	T = [120;104;93;80;71];
	P = [98;21;0;-16;-78.6];
	A = [T.^0 T.^1];
	c = A'*A\\A'*P;
	azero = -1*c(1)/c(2)
		-> 314.16...